{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7290c28c-a2de-4877-bd9c-363ec6fba89e","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** in `CreateMauiApp()` to hook into platform-specific events:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n    {\n#if ANDROID\n        events.AddAndroid(android => android\n            .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on pause */ })\n            .OnStop(activity => { /* runs on stop */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n        events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n            .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on background */ }));\n#endif\n    });\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.\n- Each platform exposes its native events (e.g., `OnResume`, `OnDestroy` on Android; `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate` on iOS).\n- This approach keeps everything in shared code — no need for platform-specific project files.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d79e6c98-1a65-46cf-8337-0e38f29caabd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development. I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":380,"requestId":"0459:149BD4:AB1F70:C3EC54:6A0279DE"},"id":"ddb84652-5a84-43f0-a8fe-1ec6e984ef59","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:52:54.973Z","parentId":"9561813b-8980-45a9-a678-0417f09e1546"}
